The HD 17092 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 17092 is a star with 6.73 times the mass of the Sun, and 13.58 times its radius. It is located 745.01 light years away from the solar system.

HD 17092 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 17092 system


HD 17092 b

HD 17092 b was discovered by the McDonald Observatory observatory, in 2007-11, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 1.31 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 17092 b is 3221.340 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 17092 b is 12.500 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 17092 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
